'''Michael Ray "Mike" Jackson''' (born December 22, 1964) is a former [[professional baseball]] player whose career spanned 19 seasons, 16 of which were spent in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). Jackson, a [[relief pitcher]] for the majority of his career, compiled a career [[earned run average]] (ERA) of 3.42, allowing 451 [[earned run]]s off of 983 [[hit (baseball)|hits]], 127 [[home run]]s, and 464 [[base on balls|walk]]s while recording 1,006 [[strikeout]]s over 1,005 [[games pitched]]. 

Although the majority of his career was spent in the major leagues, Jackson also played in [[minor league baseball]]. Standing {{convert|6|ft|1|in|cm}} and weighing {{convert|185|lb|kg}},<ref name="Bref">{{cite web |url= http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/j/jacksmi02.shtml |title=Michael Jackson Statistics and History |work=baseball-reference.com |accessdate=June 8, 2011}}</ref> he made his professional debut in 1984 for the minor-league [[Spartanburg Suns]], an affiliate of the [[Philadelphia Phillies]]. After battling arm injuries in the early 1990s, Jackson reestablished himself as a top [[relief pitcher]] for the Reds in 1995 and went on to pitch in the [[1997 World Series]] for the Indians.<ref name="Winners">{{cite book |title=Winners: how good baseball teams become great ones |last=Perry |first=Dayn |authorlink=Dayn Perry |year=2006 |publisher=John Wiley and Sons |isbn=0471721743 |page=113}}</ref> After one-year stints with the Astros, Twins, and White Sox, Jackson retired from baseball in 2005.

==Early life==
Jackson was born on December 22, 1964, in [[Houston, Texas]]. He attended high school at [[Forest Brook High School|Forest Brook]], and later attended college at [[Hill College]] in Texas.<ref>{{cite book |title=Official baseball register |first1=Mark |last1=Shimabukuro |first2=John |last2=Duxbury |year=1993 |publisher=Sporting News Publishing Co |isbn=089204456X |page=245}}</ref>

==Career==
===Philadelphia Phillies (1984<U+2013>1987)===
Jackson entered the [[Major League Baseball Draft]] in 1983, where he was selected by the Philadelphia Phillies in the 29th round. He did not sign with the Phillies, and reentered the draft in 1984 where was again drafted by the Phillies in the second round of the January Secondary amateur draft. Jackson signed a [[United States Dollar|$]]60,000 contract with the club on April 27, 1984.<ref name="Bref" />

Jackson began playing [[minor league baseball]] for the single-A [[Spartanburg Suns]], a minor league affiliate of the Phillies, in 1984. Over 80.2 [[innings pitched]], Jackson recorded an [[earned run average]] (ERA) of 2.68, third best on his team. While batting, he recorded the best [[batting average]] and [[slugging percentage]] on the team, hitting .368 and slugging .526.<ref name="Spartanburg1984">{{cite web |url= http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=b061868e |title=1984 Spartanburg Suns Statistics |work=baseball-reference.com |accessdate=June 9, 2011}}</ref>

Jackson continued his minor league career in 1985, playing for the [[Peninsula Pilots]] of the [[Carolina League]]. Unlike the previous year where he [[starting pitcher|started]] all 14 games he pitched, Jackson roughly split the 1985 season between starting games and serving as a [[Relief pitcher|reliever]], starting 18 games but pitching in 31.<ref name="Spartanburg1984" /><ref name="Spartanburg1985">{{cite web |url= http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=d69261a0 |title=1985 Peninsula Pilots Statistics |work=baseball-reference.com |accessdate=June 11, 2011}}</ref> For the season, Jackson led the Pilots in [[Loss (baseball)|losses]], with nine, while allowing the most [[hit (baseball)|hits]], [[run (baseball)|runs]], and [[earned run]]s among team members.<ref name="Spartanburg1985" />

In 1986, he played in three different leagues: [[Double-A (baseball)|Double-A]], [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]], and in the Major Leagues. In Double-A, Jackson played for the [[Reading Phillies]], recording a 1.66 ERA over 43.1 innings pitched.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=807417a8 |title=1986 Reading Phillies Statistics |work=baseball-reference.com |accessdate=June 12, 2011}}</ref> He played Triple-A ball for the [[Portland Beavers]] before making his major league debut for the Philadelphia Phillies on August 11, 1986. For his debut, Jackson pitched a [[Glossary of baseball (P)#perfect inning|perfect inning]] in relief of [[Dan Schatzeder]] in a game against the [[New York Mets]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1986/B08110PHI1986.htm |title=Retrosheet Boxscore: New York Mets 8, Philadelphia Phillies 4 |work=[[Retrosheet]] |accessdate=June 12, 2011}}</ref> Jackson finished the 1986 Major League season with a 3.38 ERA, allowing five runs off of 12 hits and becoming the seventh youngest player in the [[National League]] that year.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL/1986-other-leaders.shtml |title=1986 National League Awards, All-Stars, & More Leaders |work=baseball-reference.com |accessdate=June 12, 2011}}</ref>

Jackson played almost the entire 1987 season for the Philadelphia Phillies, also making two starts for the [[Maine Guides]]. During the season, he compiled a 4.20 ERA with three wins and 10 losses. After the season, on December 9, 1987, Jackson was traded, along with [[Glenn Wilson (baseball)|Glenn Wilson]] and Dave Brundage, to the [[Seattle Mariners]]. In exchange, the Phillies received pitcher [[Tim Fortugno]], who never made a professional appearance for the Phillies, and an [[outfielder]], [[Phil Bradley]].<ref name="Westcott">{{cite book |title=Tales from the Phillies Dugout |last=Westcott |first=Rich |year=2006 |publisher=Sports Publishing LLC |isbn=1596700378 |page=124}}</ref> Author Rich Westcott would later call Jackson "a good one who got away" in reference to the Phillies trade.<ref name="Westcott" />

===Seattle Mariners (1988<U+2013>1991)===
From 1988 to 1991, Jackson played for the Seattle Mariners. In 1988 and 1989, Jackson finished in the top ten in the [[American League]] for most [[games pitched]], with 62 and 65, respectively, while recording a 2.90 ERA over 198.2 innings pitched for the two seasons.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/j/jacksmi02.shtml#1988-1989-sum:pitching_simple |title=Michael Jackson pitching statistics, 1988<U+2013>1989 |work=baseball-reference.com |accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> In 1991, while facing the [[Kansas City Royals]], he allowed [[Stu Cole]]'s only Major League hit while pitching in the bottom of the 13th inning.<ref>{{cite book |title=One Hit Wonders: Baseball Stories |last=Rose |first=George |year=2004 |publisher=[[iUniverse]] |isbn=059531807X |page=176}}</ref>

After spending four seasons with the Mariners, Jackson was traded, along with [[Bill Swift]] and [[Dave Burba]], to the [[San Francisco Giants]]. The Mariners, in return for Swift, Burba, and Jackson, acquired outfielder [[Kevin Mitchell (baseball)|Kevin Mitchell]] and pitcher [[Mike Remlinger]].<ref name="Bref" /> This trade received criticism, being called "possibly the worst trade in [Mariners] history."<ref>{{cite book |title=Baseball's Greatest Series: Yankees, Mariners, and the 1995 Matchup That Changed History |last=Donnelly |first=Chris |year=2010 |publisher=[[Rutgers University Press]] |isbn=0813546621 |page=21}}</ref>

===San Francisco Giants (1992<U+2013>1994)===
Jackson, now with a salary of $1,666,667<ref name="Bref" />, made his debut for the Giants on April 7, 1992, in a game against the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1992/B04070LAN1992.htm |title=Los Angeles Dodgers 3, San Francisco Giants 0 |work=retrosheet.org |accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref> Jackson allowed one [[base on balls|walk]] in one inning pitched, while finishing the 1992 season with a 3.73 ERA, 80 strikeouts, and one [[save (baseball)|save]]. He led his team in games pitched, with 67, the second highest total in his Giants career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/player/stats/_/id/1809/mike-jackson|title=Mike Jackson|work=ESPN|accessdate=July 31, 2011}}</ref>

In 1993 he led the Major Leagues in games pitched, with 81, while also leading the Majors in [[hold (baseball)|holds]], with 33.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Holway |first1=John |year=1994 |title=Middle Relievers Deserve More Credit in the Majors |journal=[[Baseball Digest]] |volume=53 |issue=5 |page=21 |publisher=Lakeside Publishing Co |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=lCsDAAAAMBAJ&source=gbs_navlinks_s |accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> The 1994 MLB season was [[1994<U+2013>95 Major League Baseball strike|shortened]] to 115 games for the Giants; however, over 36 games pitched, Jackson led National League relievers in ERA (1.49), opponents average (.164), and hits per 9.0 innings pitched (4.9) while finishing second in strikeouts per 9.0 innings pitched (10.84).<ref name="MLB.bio">{{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player.jsp?player_id=116436 |title=Mike Jackson Stats, Bio, Photos, Highlights |work=MLB.com |accessdate=June 21, 2011}} (Note: Click bio for information)</ref> The already shortened season season was again shortened for Jackson due to [[tendinitis]] in his right elbow. This lead to two stints on the disabled list: one from June 17 until July 2, and another from July 6 until the end of the season.<ref name="MLB.bio" /> On October 17, 1994, Jackson was granted [[free agent|free agency]].<ref name="Bref" />

===Cincinnati Reds (1995)===
Jackson signed with the [[Cincinnati Reds]] on April 8, 1995. Again he struggled with injury, and was placed on the disabled list once for tendinitis in his right shoulder and once for a strained [[Human rib cage|rib cage]] muscle.<ref name="MLB.bio" /> In his only year with the club, Jackson posted a team-best 2.39 ERA, while recording 41 strikeouts over 40 games.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/CIN/1995.shtml |title=1995 Cincinnati Reds Batting, Pitching, & Fielding Statistics |work=baseball-reference.com |accessdate=June 16, 2011}}</ref> Jackson and the Reds made the playoffs, winning the [[National League Divisional Series]] but losing the [[National League Championship Series]] to the [[Atlanta Braves]] in four games. Jackson was granted free agency on November 3, 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/CIN/1995-transactions.shtml|title=1995 Cincinnati Reds Trades and Transactions|work=baseball-reference.com|accessdate=July 31, 2011}}</ref>

===Seattle Mariners (1996)===
In 1996, Jackson signed a $1,200,000 contract, which included a $400,000 earned bonus, with the Seattle Mariners. Jackson averaged nearly nine strikeouts per 9.0 innings pitched (70 strikeouts/72.0 innings pitched).<ref name="MLB.bio" /> After the season, ''[[Baseball Digest]]'' called Jackson "a competent and underappreciated setup man".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Crasnick |first1=Jerry |year=1996 |title='Burnout' Problems, Always Threat to Middle Relievers |journal=Baseball Digest |volume=55 |issue=12 |pages=68{{dash}}73 |publisher=Lakeside Publishing Co |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=wy0DAAAAMBAJ&source=gbs_navlinks_s |accessdate=June 17, 2011}}</ref> The Mariners did not resign Jackson, on the grounds that Jackson's new contract would be too expensive.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997/oct/26/sports/sp-47077 |title=Letting Jackson Go Not Worth It for Mariners |author=Mike DiGiovanna and Mike Downey |date=October 26, 1997 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Eddy Hartenstein]] |accessdate=June 17, 2011}}</ref>

===Cleveland Indians (1997<U+2013>1999)===
In 1997, Jackson signed a three year, six million dollar contract with the [[Cleveland Indians]]. Jackson served as the primary [[Setup pitcher|setup man]] to [[closer (baseball)|closer]] [[Jos<U+00E9> Mesa]] for the first half of the season, but took over the closer position while Mesa answered to charges of rape.<ref name="Winners" /> Finishing the year with a 86<U+2013>75 record, the Indians finished first in the [[American League Central]] and made the playoffs. After winning against the [[New York Yankees]] in the [[American League Divisional Series]] (ALDS) and the [[Baltimore Orioles]] in the [[American League Championship Series]] (ALCS), the Indians played in the [[World Series]] against the [[Florida Marlins]]. In the World Series, Jackson recorded an ERA of 1.93 over four games pitched, although the Indians lost the World Series, four games to three.

After the Indians traded Mesa to the Giants in July 1998, Jackson became the Indians primary closer, recording 40 saves over 64.0 innings pitched and leading the team in [[games finished]], saves, and games pitched.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/CLE/1998.shtml |title=1998 Cleveland Indians Batting, Pitching, & Fielding Statistics |work=baseball-reference.com |accessdate=June 21, 2011}}</ref> The Indians again made the postseason, but were eliminated by the New York Yankees in the ALCS.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Yankee Encyclopedia|last1=Gallagher|first1=Mark|last2=LeConte|first2=Walter|year=2003|publisher=Sports Publishing LLC|page=460}}</ref>

Jackson finished the 1999 season with Cleveland, ranking fourth in the American League in saves, with 39.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1999-pitching-leaders.shtml|title=1999 American League Pitching Leaders|work=baseball-reference.com|accessdate=August 1, 2011}}</ref> Jackson recorded his 100th career save against the [[Minnesota Twins]] on April 11, and made his 800th career appearance on July 3 against the Kansas City Royals<ref name="MLB.bio" /> before he was granted free agency on October 28 of that year.

===2000 onward===
Jackson signed with the Phillies in 2000 but did not pitch due to discomfort in his right shoulder the first time Jackson [[warming up|warmed up]] to pitch in a game for Philadelphia.<ref name="MLB.bio" /> On May 26, Jackson had season-ending [[arthroscopic surgery]] to repair a [[SLAP tear]] in his right shoulder.<ref name="MLB.bio" />

Jackson signed with the [[Houston Astros]] the next year. The Astros, [[National League Central]] champions, earned a spot in the playoffs, but were eliminated by the Atlanta Braves in the Divisional series. After his season with the Astros, in 2002, Jackson signed as a non-roster invitee with the [[Minnesota Twins]], helping them to finish 94<U+2013>67 and leading them to a playoff appearance, where he recorded a 27.00 ERA over three games pitched in the [[American League Championship Series]] (ALCS). The Twins lost the ALCS in five games.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/2002_ALCS.shtml |title=2002 League Championship Series{{ndash}} Anaheim Angels over Minnesota Twins (4-1) |work=baseball-reference.com |accessdate=June 19, 2011}}</ref> Jackson was granted free agency later that year.

On January 29, 2003, Jackson signed for the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]], but did not play a major league or minor league game for the franchise. The Diamondbacks released Jackson on March 29, 2003, before the season began.<ref name="Bref" /> Jackson later stated:

{{quote|I know it's a numbers game and nothing I could control, but I was disappointed that I had to sit at home [for the 2003 season]. If teams want to base their decision about me on [[spring training]] as opposed to what I<U+2019>ve accomplished over the years, then I don<U+2019>t know what to say.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20040222&content_id=640136&vkey=spt2004news&fext=.jsp&c_id=null |archivedate=June 19, 2011 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5zZTDX3bk |title=Jackson rested and determined |first=Scott |last=Merkin |work=MLB.com |year=2004 |accessdate=June 19, 2011}}</ref>}}

In his last professional season, Jackson signed as a [[non-roster invitee]] with the [[Chicago White Sox]]. For the season, Jackson recorded an ERA of 5.01, allowing 31 runs over 46.2 innings pitched.<ref name="Bref" /> The White Sox released Jackson on September 2, 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com:8080/teams/CHW/2004-transactions.shtml|title=2004 Chicago White Sox Trades and Transactions|work=baseball-reference.com|accessdate=July 31, 2011}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Jackson is married to Tammy Jackson and has four children: Lindsey, Ryan, Amber and Michael.<ref name="MLB.bio" />

